## Figure 1.

In Fig. 2 are shown the effects of treatment with {{ drug.name }} in the 597 patients who had been treated previously on other antihypertensive agents but had been uncontrolled ({{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} >140/90 mm Hg) while on the previous therapy. The values shown in Fig. 2 are for the effects of {{ drug.name }} after the previous therapies had been discontinued, and are shown separately for the major antihypertensive drug classes that were previously administered. All changes were statistically significant (P < .001 for all values). In Fig. 3 are shown the changes in systolic and diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} for patients divided into groups based on age, sex, or ethnicity. All within group changes for both systolic and diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} were significant (P < .001 for all). For systolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}, the between group differences within the age, sex, and ethnic categories were significant (P < .001 for all). For diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}, all within group differences were also significant (P< .001 for all). Likewise, the difference between the younger and older groups and between white and African American patients were also significant (P < .001 for each), but the difference between men and women was not significant.
